To enhance its future-ready FMCG portfolio in the retail sector in India, ITC has launched nearly 100 superior and differentiated products annually, focusing on segments such as Health and Nutrition, Hygiene, Protection and Care, Convenience, On-the-Go, and Indulgence. Sustained margin expansion was achieved through premiumization, streamlined operations, agile cost management, and operational leverage, leading to an average margin expansion of 100 basis points per year over the past seven years. ITC’s FMCG products now reach 250 million households, generating consumer spending of Rs. 32,500 crore. The ITC Next strategy strengthens structural competitiveness and supports ITC's goal to become the No. 1 player in this industry.

Despite global challenges and subdued domestic consumption, ITC delivered a resilient performance in the past year. Gross revenue, excluding the Agri-Business, which faced regulatory trade restrictions due to food security concerns and inflation, increased by 6.8 percent. Profit after tax (PAT) for the year grew by 8.9 percent.

Over the last two years, overall revenue and PAT grew at a compound annual growth rate (CAGR) of 9.9 percent and 16.5 percent, respectively. The FMCG-Others segment saw a growth of 14.5 percent, while Segment Profit Before Interest and Tax (PBIT) grew by an impressive 38.8 percent. Despite near-term challenges in the FMCG industry, ITC’s innovative capacity, future-ready portfolio, resilient supply chains, digital investments, and focus on penetration-led growth position the company well in the addressable market potential of Rs 5 lakh crore in its operating categories.

ITC Contributing to ‘Make in India’ Vision

ITC continues to invest in building world-class infrastructure and ecosystems linked to its products and services, contributing significantly to the 'Make in India' vision. Despite its growing footprint, nearly 90 percent of all raw materials are locally procured. The extensive manufacturing network of over 200 factories supports local entrepreneurship and sustainable livelihoods. In the last two years alone, investments in three owned luxury hotels, eight state-of-the-art manufacturing facilities (including those under the PLI scheme), and the doubling of ITC’s distribution infrastructure have generated significant livelihoods. Ongoing investments in three state-of-the-art manufacturing facilities and an IT and Knowledge Centre will further enhance this potential. ITC engages with over 6,000 MSMEs, focusing extensively on upgrading their technology, quality, and skills, believing that enterprises are only as strong as their value chains.

ITC’s Digital Investments Transform Operations

ITC's digital investments drive a digital-first culture, transforming all facets of operations—from insighting to product development, smart sourcing to on-time efficient delivery, and superior brand engagement and marketing through real-time content, connect, and commerce. An intelligent big data ecosystem leveraging Industry 4.0, AI/ML, and GenAI is redefining consumer experiences and operational efficiencies. ITC’s Trade Marketing and Distribution infrastructure has evolved into a smart omnichannel network, doubling market coverage, with three out of four retailers carrying ITC's FMCG products. ITC has also launched six exclusive D2C platforms. The e-B2B platform, UNNATI, continues to scale rapidly, covering nearly 7 lakh outlets.

ITC’s Investment Outlay of Rs 20,000 Crore

Despite market challenges, ITC’s strategic investments across all its businesses enhance structural competitiveness and build an enterprise poised for future opportunities. Reflecting unwavering confidence in the India growth story, ITC has committed an investment outlay of about Rs 20,000 crore in the medium term.

New Delhi-based home decor brand Dusaan has made a significant expansion into the furniture category, introducing over 300 products. This new line aims to broaden Dusaan's home decor offerings and meet the diverse needs of its growing customer base.

Dusaan is targeting a fivefold increase in growth within the furniture category by the end of 2024. The company is leveraging its strong market presence and customer loyalty to achieve this ambitious goal.

“Furniture is among the primary needs for every household, and we are excited to add this new line of products for our customers. With the addition of furniture on Dusaan, we are taking another step towards making home shopping easier for Indian consumers,” said Simran Kohli, Founder, Dusaan.

The newly launched furniture collection includes products from 20 domestic brands that emphasize eco-conscious designs and sustainable materials. This aligns with Dusaan's commitment to promoting environmentally friendly practices. The company plans to expand this category further by December 2024, incorporating even more options for its customers.

Dusaan intends to tap into its existing customer base for the furniture category, focusing especially on those building or revamping their homes in Tier-I and Tier-II cities. The company believes this strategic move will help it capitalize on the increasing demand for stylish and sustainable home furnishings in these rapidly growing markets.

The collection features a wide range of furniture items, including desks, beds, tables, racks, table trolleys, chairs, poufs and stools, TV units, shelves, and storage units, with prices ranging from Rs. 5,000 to Rs. 40,000. This diverse selection ensures that there is something for every customer, catering to various tastes and budgets.

The new furniture category is already live on Dusaan’s platform, and the company is in the process of onboarding international furniture brands to further enhance its offerings. This move is expected to attract a wider audience and provide customers with access to high-quality furniture from around the world.

Founded in 2022, Dusaan currently features over 400 brands, including more than 50 international ones. The e-commerce platform is also exploring collaborations with additional global brands, particularly those that are women-owned and eco-friendly. This focus on diversity and sustainability reflects Dusaan's broader mission to create a positive impact through its business practices.

Nestlé India Ltd reported a 6.9 percent rise in net profit to Rs. 746.60 crore for the quarter ending June 2024, up from Rs. 698.34 crore during the same period last year, according to the company's regulatory filing.

Revenue from product sales grew by 3.75 percent to Rs. 4,792.97 crore, compared to Rs. 4,619.50 crore in the previous year. Despite a tough market environment with slower consumption growth, Nestlé India saw positive results.

"Despite external challenges such as lower consumption growth, concerns about continued food inflation, and volatile commodity prices, we have delivered growth across our product groups. Almost a fourth of our growth has been mix and volume-led, and we hope to strengthen this trend in the coming months," said Suresh Narayanan, Chairman and Managing Director of Nestlé India. He also noted that "5 of our top 12 brands grew double-digit."

Domestic sales increased by 4.24 percent to Rs. 4,608.50 crore, up from Rs. 4,420.77 crore the previous year. E-commerce sales continued their upward trend, contributing 7.5 percent to domestic sales with double-digit growth. The company also saw strong performance in quick commerce, driven by brands like KitKat, Nescafe, and Maggi Masala-ae-Magic.

The organized trade channels experienced double-digit growth, particularly in value-added noodles, beverages, and premium products. The Out of Home segment also showed strong growth. Innovations in prepared dishes and cooking aids contributed 30 percent of the growth for the quarter, with KitKat and the milk products and nutrition portfolio maintaining strong performance.

However, exports fell by 7.17 percent to Rs. 184.47 crore, though new SKUs were introduced in markets including the USA, Canada, and the Middle East. Total expenses for the quarter increased by 2.7 percent to Rs. 3,844.01 crores, while revenue from operations, including other revenue, rose by 3.33 percent to Rs. 4,813.95 crores. Total income grew by 3.64 percent to Rs. 4,853.07 crore.

As part of its Rurban strategy, Nestlé India focused on enhancing distribution infrastructure, adding over 800 new touchpoints and expanding coverage to 2.05 lakh villages.

Looking ahead, Nestlé India anticipates continued challenges with high commodity prices for coffee and cocoa, structural cost increases for cereals and grains, and relative stability in milk prices, packaging, and edible oils. This quarter marks the first financial report since Nestlé India changed its fiscal year to align with April 1 to March 31.

Nestlé India shares were trading at Rs. 2,462.20 on the BSE, reflecting a 3.21 percent decline from the previous close.

Godrej Interio, a leading name in home and office furniture and part of the Godrej Enterprises Group, has unveiled revealing insights into India’s culinary preferences and kitchen dynamics through its latest 'HomeScapes' survey. The study, which explores city-specific trends, identifies Chennai and Lucknow as the top cities for home food enthusiasts.

According to the survey, approximately 31 percent of respondents in Lucknow and 28 percent in Chennai view their kitchens and dining rooms as primary spaces for culinary experimentation. This trend aligns with predictions from the Godrej Food Trends Report 2024, which highlights a growing interest in homemade, authentic masalas and condiments. Notably, 41 percent of the respondents in Lucknow and 37 percent in Chennai are keen on reviving family cooking traditions, with Hyderabad showing the highest enthusiasm at 70 percent.

Hyderabad leads the nation in adopting open kitchen concepts, with 73 percent of respondents believing it fosters a more engaging cooking and dining experience. Chennai and Lucknow follow suit with 59 percent and 54 percent support respectively. At the dining table, Chennai and Lucknow stand out for their engaging mealtime interactions, with 60 percent of respondents in Chennai and 53 percent in Lucknow enjoying playful debates about seating arrangements. In contrast, Hyderabad, while leading in kitchen design preferences, shows a different dynamic, with only 36 percent of respondents participating in such interactions.

Kolkata presents a unique contrast; while its percentage of home foodies (24 percent) is close to the national average (25 percent), it shows the lowest engagement in cooking and dining activities. An overwhelming 83 percent of Kolkata respondents prefer separate kitchens to maintain a clean living space.

Swapneel Nagarkar, Senior Vice President & Business Head, Godrej Interio said, “The 'HomeScapes' research highlights the profound emotional bond individuals share with their kitchens and dining spaces. Our insights reveal the diverse culinary habits across cities, reflecting how people interact with their kitchens and dining spaces. At Godrej Interio, we are committed to creating furniture that enhances these experiences, ensuring that homes remain the heart of culinary creativity, and family bonding and cater to the diverse needs of Indian households, from open-concept kitchens to multifunctional dining areas.”

The "HomeScapes" survey was conducted with respondents from seven cities, including Bengaluru, Chennai, Delhi, Hyderabad, Kolkata, Mumbai, and Lucknow.
